hands_on_practices.solution:
We model the deeply bound fermion pairs as bosons of mass $M_B=2m$ and density $n_B=n/2$, with boson-boson scattering length 
$$a_B=C\,a_s.$$
The low-energy interaction strength is 
$$g=\frac{4\pi\hbar^2\,a_B}{M_B}
=\frac{4\pi\hbar^2\,C\,a_s}{2m}
=\frac{2\pi\hbar^2\,C\,a_s}{m}.$$
At $T=0$, the bosonic mean-field chemical potential is 
$$\mu_B=g\,n_B
=\frac{2\pi\hbar^2\,C\,a_s}{m}\;\frac{n}{2}
=\frac{\pi\hbar^2\,C\,a_s\,n}{m}.$$
Each boson corresponds to two fermions, so the fermionic chemical-potential shift is half of $\mu_B$:
$$\delta\mu=\frac{\mu_B}{2}
=\frac{1}{2}\,\frac{\pi\hbar^2\,C\,a_s\,n}{m}
=\frac{\pi\hbar^2\,C\,a_s\,n}{2m}\,. $$
